---
import DocsLayout from '../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { label: 'Why Bedrock', href: '#why-bedrock' },
  { label: 'Proven Under Load', href: '#battle-tested' },
  { label: 'The Toolkit', href: '#the-toolkit' },
  { label: 'Designed in Layers', href: '#designed-in-layers' },
  { label: 'Built to Grow', href: '#built-to-grow' },
  { label: 'Start Building', href: '#start-building' }
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="sf-bedrock — enterprise Apex that stays readable"
  description="sf-bedrock is a Salesforce architecture toolkit: dependency injection, tests that run without a database, and clean trigger patterns — proven in Fortune 100 orgs."
  eyebrow="Salesforce Architecture Toolkit"
  sections={sections}
>
  <Fragment slot="header">
    <h1>Apex that scales without the ceremony.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      sf-bedrock is a foundation for enterprise Apex: dependency injection, unit
      tests that never touch the database, and trigger patterns that stay clean
      under load. It keeps high-volume orgs safe without making everyday code
      heavy — and it reads the way the engineer who owns it would write it.
    </p>
    <div class="pill-row" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
      <span class="pill">Dependency Injection</span>
      <span class="pill">Database-Free Tests</span>
      <span class="pill">Clean Triggers</span>
      <span class="pill">Human-Maintainable</span>
    </div>
    <div class="pill-row" style="margin-top: 1.5rem; gap: 0.6rem;">
      <a class="button button-primary" href="/getting-started">Get Started</a>
      <a class="button button-secondary" href="/test-data">Explore the API</a>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <section class="doc-section" id="why-bedrock">
    <h2>Why Bedrock</h2>
    <p>
      Enterprise Salesforce usually forces a trade: heavy frameworks that make
      code testable but obscure, or lean code that reads well until the test
      suite grinds against the database. Bedrock takes neither side. It is a
      small set of dependency-injection seams that keep production code direct
      and tests fast — no rewrite of how your team already works.
    </p>
    <div class="doc-grid">
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Tests without a database</h3>
        <p>
          Mock DML, SOQL, and cache so unit tests never touch the database.
          Suites that took minutes finish in seconds.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Readable by humans</h3>
        <p>
          Minimalist, low-ceremony Apex. The seams live in your tests, not
          tangled through your business logic.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Safe at volume</h3>
        <p>
          Bulk-safe staged DML, grouped upserts, and recursion-minded trigger
          design built for high-throughput orgs.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="doc-card">
        <h3>Composable, not monolithic</h3>
        <p>
          Adopt one tool or all of them. Each stands on its own and composes with
          the rest — none takes over your architecture.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="battle-tested">
    <h2>Proven Under Real Load</h2>
    <p>
      These patterns started in Fortune 100 Salesforce orgs — high-volume,
      high-scrutiny environments where flaky tests, recursive triggers, and
      governor limits are daily realities, not edge cases. Bedrock is what
      held up under that pressure, packaged so any team can adopt it.
    </p>
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Developer-first, by design</strong>
      <p>
        The goal is automation that protects the org and still makes sense to the
        people who own it. Every abstraction earns its place — if it makes
        everyday work heavier, it does not ship.
      </p>
    </div>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Built for scale</strong>
        <span>Shaped by orgs with millions of records and unforgiving daily volume.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tests that mean something</strong>
        <span>Assertions prove real behavior and mutations, not just coverage.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Org-protective</strong>
        <span>Designed to stay inside platform limits, not race against them.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="the-toolkit">
    <h2>The Toolkit</h2>
    <p>
      Eight focused tools, each documented with the contract, real examples, and
      the testing path. They stand alone and compose together.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/test-data">TestData</a></strong>
        <span>Focused records with mock Ids — and even normally read-only fields set — without DML or setup bloat.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/dml">DML</a></strong>
        <span>Every write behind one injectable facade. Capture and assert operations in tests with DMLMock.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/query">Query</a></strong>
        <span>Swap SOQL for staged results. Prove data-access behavior without a database — single or sequential responses.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/platform-cache">PlatformCache</a></strong>
        <span>Org and session Platform Cache behind a mockable seam — the part of the platform that is notoriously hard to test, finally testable.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/record-buffer">RecordBuffer</a></strong>
        <span>Stage inserts and updates across a transaction, then flush grouped, deduplicated upserts at a controlled point.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/trigger-handler">TriggerHandler</a></strong>
        <span>Context detection and dispatch handled; you override only the before/after hooks that matter.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/feature-flag">FeatureFlag</a></strong>
        <span>Metadata-driven toggles that fail closed, with one-line overrides for tests.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/generic">Generic</a></strong>
        <span>Tame untyped JSON with path access, type coercion, and typed SObject conversion.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="designed-in-layers">
    <h2>Designed in Layers</h2>
    <p>
      Separation of concerns is the organizing principle. Bedrock gives each
      layer a home so logic stops leaking across boundaries — and so the next
      engineer can find it where they expect.
    </p>
    <ul class="token-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Schema</strong>
        <span>SObjects, metadata, and settings that define the system's shape.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Domain</strong>
        <span>Triggers and record lifecycle behavior, coordinated by small handlers.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Selector</strong>
        <span>Reusable, testable query logic built on Query.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Service</strong>
        <span>Cross-record orchestration and the business behavior that matters.</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>UI Layer</strong>
        <span>Components and thin controllers that adapt to the glass and delegate complexity to services.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="built-to-grow">
    <h2>Built to Grow</h2>
    <p>
      The foundation ships today. The roadmap extends the same approach into
      query encapsulation and a shared async foundation — delivered one
      deliberate, inspectable piece at a time, never as a speculative
      megaframework.
    </p>
    <div class="pill-row">
      <span class="pill">Selector</span>
      <span class="pill">Selector.Cached</span>
      <span class="pill">Async</span>
      <span class="pill">Event</span>
      <span class="pill">Scheduler</span>
      <span class="pill">LimitsService</span>
    </div>
    <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
      Async, Event, and Scheduler will share one foundation while keeping
      separate execution pools, and consult a limit-aware service before running
      work — so framework automation protects org health instead of threatening
      it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-section" id="start-building">
    <h2>Start Building</h2>
    <p>
      Stand up the docs locally, then start with the testing foundation —
      <code>TestData</code>, <code>DML</code>, and <code>Query</code> — and feel
      how fast a Bedrock test suite runs.
    </p>
    <div class="utility-panel">
      <div>
        <h3>Ready in minutes</h3>
        <p>
          Begin with the getting-started guide, or jump straight into the API
          that anchors every Bedrock test.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="pill-row" style="gap: 0.6rem;">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/getting-started">Getting Started</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/test-data">TestData API</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
